 names from that team and construct an HTML unordered list with each member as a list item. Finally, return the generated HTML.\n\nI'm reconsidering the XPath approach for finding teams by name. Direct XPath with string matching like `.//team[name='{team_name}']` could fail with special characters. A safer method is to iterate through all teams and compare the name element's text directly, avoiding injection issues. This approach—looping through teams and checking if the name matches—is more robust than embedding the team name directly in an XPath expression.\n\nNow I'm writing out the complete Flask application with the XML data embedded. The route accepts a team_name query parameter, searches for the matching team by iterating through the XML structure, and returns an HTML list of members. If no team_name is provided, it returns a 400 error; if the team isn't found, it returns 404. The function safely extracts member names and formats them as list items.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5110,"cache_read_input_tokens":24095,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5110},"output_tokens":7,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9e292084-121b-45af-bf83-1509fe3a2504","uuid":"334b08db-a097-4902-8d35-4d6fcce8721f","request_id":"req_011CbdNhkzbn31ZTvFLcT2sr"}
